<div class="entry-content primary-content-column columns small-12 medium-8">
<aside class="series-card row">
<div class="series-image small-4 columns">
<a href='https://truthout.org/series/human-rights-and-global-wrongs/'>
<img width="200" height="113" src="https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/2018_0129n-hrgw-200x113.jpg" class="attachment-hd_thumbnail size-hd_thumbnail" alt="Human Rights and Global Wrongs" srcset="https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/2018_0129n-hrgw-200x113.jpg 200w, https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/2018_0129n-hrgw-400x225.jpg 400w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" />
</a>
</div>
<div class="series-info small-8 columns">
<p class='meta-label'>Part of the Series</p>
<h5 class='series-title'><a href='https://truthout.org/series/human-rights-and-global-wrongs/'>Human Rights and Global Wrongs</a></h5>
</div>
</aside>
<p>Today, the House of Representatives is poised to adopt a resolution overturning Donald Trump&rsquo;s trumped-up <span><a href="https://www.whitehouse.gov/presidential-actions/presidential-proclamation-declaring-national-emergency-concerning-southern-border-united-states/">&ldquo;national emergency&rdquo; proclamation</a></span>, in which he claims authority to fulfill his campaign promise to build a wall at the southern border.</p>
<p>The <span><a href="https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/50/1622">National Emergencies Act</a></span> requires Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell to bring the House resolution to a vote within 18 days. In order to prevail in the Senate, four Republicans would have to defy Trump. If the bill passes both houses of Congress, Trump has pledged to veto it and there is little chance Congress could muster the two-thirds necessary to override his veto.</p>
<p>In the likely event the legislature fails to void Trump&rsquo;s &ldquo;emergency&rdquo; declaration, the judicial branch will have the opportunity to check and balance the executive. Six lawsuits have already been filed in federal courts around the country. They quote Trump&rsquo;s own words to demonstrate that even he doesn&rsquo;t believe there&rsquo;s a bona fide emergency. The suits claim Trump violated the Constitution&rsquo;s Separation of Powers mandate by circumventing the will of Congress, which has rejected Trump&rsquo;s $5.7 billion demand for his wall. And they allege violation of the National Environmental Policy Act.</p><div class="truth-post-content-high  inline-callout-container" id="truth-255792"><aside class=" callout inline-callout callout--subscribe callout--dark" id="truth-255397">
<h2>The stories you care about, right at your fingertips</h2>
<p>Get <em>Truthout&rsquo;</em>s daily edition delivered to your inbox.</p>
